 Controlling farming-based nonpoint water pollution: 
 costs of starting the Maryland Water Quality 
 Improvement Act of 1998* 
 Doug Parker* 
 Farming-based and useful thing/valuable supply Money flow, University of Maryland, College Park, MD 20742, USA 
 
 Abstract 
 The Maryland Water Quality Improvement Act of 1998 (WQIA) tries to create (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) and other benefits to the 
 Chesapeake Bay through reductions in nonpoint source nutrient pollution. This paper carefully studies the money-based effects of the 
 WQIA on farming-based users of (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) (commercial (material that makes plants grow better)s or animal poop/fertilizers) and on (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers in the state of 
 Maryland. The net money-based effects to each of these groups are guessed along with some discussion of the distribution of 
 the hits/effects. Recognition of the distribution of the hits/effects allows for the test of possible policies to address negative 
 hits/effects. Added/more sections of the WQIA are discussed in terms of their ability to shift the distribution of the hits/effects or 
 to provide partial payment to those most affected. The WQIA is the most (serving to severely limit or control) farming-based (pollution that comes from a wide area) 
 control law in the US. While the WQIA only controls nutrient use in the state of Maryland, other states, as well as the federal 
 government, are watching how this law is used. Many states are thinking about almost the same  laws. At the national level, the 
 United States Department of Farming and the United States (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) Protection (service business/government unit/power/functioning) have issued draft guidelines 
 that will control (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) from animal operations in much the same way as the WQIA. Therefore, analyses of the money-based 
 hits/effects of the WQIA may be important in shaping policies in other states and at the national level. Â© 2000 Elsevier Science 
 B.V. All rights reserved. 
 JEL classification: Q20 
 Keywords: Non point source pollution; Water quality; Nutrient management; Animal waste management 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 Runoff and leaking from farming-based fields are a 
 major source of nonpoint source pollution (US (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) Protection (service business/government unit/power/functioning), 1996). Contaminated 
 (underground water that supplies wells) can have a bad effect when con- 
 
