 cropping in winter months (Helfand and House, 1995; 
 Wu and Segerson, 1995; Suppalla eta!., 1995; Lichtenberg et a!., 1994). Since most phosphorus from 
 farming-based lands is moved with (material that sinks in liquid), (material that sinks in liquid) control has been the major focus for phosphorus 
 control. What's more, because phosphorus binds to 
 the soil, phosphorus has not been a (underground water that supplies wells) concern. So, most research on phosphorus 
 management has focused on the control of (materials that sink in liquids). 
 (material that sinks in liquid) control measures that have been tested 
 include cover crops, buffer strips, no or low till, and 
 the use of polymers (Wu and Babcock, 1998; Hanson 
 eta!., 1993; Yiridoe and Weersink, 1998; Parker and 
 Caswell, 1999). 
 Increased densities in the (land-area-based/location) distribution 
 of animal production have led to excess amounts of 
 (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) in animal producing areas (Letson et a!., 
 1998). Since most animal waste is applied to the land 
 as a source of (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.), the (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) of the animal industry has created a situation of gross excesses 
 of certain (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) being land applied. Recent soil 
 science research has shown that very high phosphorus 
 levels can lead to (able to be dissolved in something) phosphorus runoff (Sims, 
 1998). So, phosphorus control in animal intense 
 areas must go beyond (material that sinks in liquid) keeping/holding onto/remembering. Recent 
 research on phosphorus management has focused on 
 current and other choice uses of animal wastes (Jacobs and Casler, 1979; Govindasamy and Cochran, 
 1995; Bosch and Napit, 1992; Parker, 1998). This 
 paper thinks about/believes nitrogen and phosphorus as part of a 
 (related to a large area) nutrient management plan. 
 
 2. Concerns for the Chesapeake Bay 
 In August of 1997, the Chesapeake Bay experienced 
 a few poisonous  outbreaks of the germ Pfiesteria piscicida. The germ was responsible for a few fish 
 kills (each killing thousands of fish) in rivers on the 
 Lower Shore of the Bay. Local fishermen and residents 
 complained of (feeling of spinning around and almost falling) and memory loss after exposure to those waters. The State of Maryland responded 
 by closing a few rivers and issuing health warnings 
 to local residents. Pjiesteria had been present in the 
 Neuse River in North Carolina for a few years and, 
 this way, there was the beginning of a scientific understanding of the germ. Maryland's fast response 
 to the germ helped scientific question (or investigation) into the life 
 
 cycle of the germ and the conditions under which it 
 becomes a poisonous  danger/risk to the waters in which it exists. 
 A scientific panel of experts was brought together to test the state of knowledge about the germ 
 (Cambridge Agreement, 1997). This panel ended/decided 
 that high levels of (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) in the Bay's waters, especially phosphorus, had combined with warm waters, 
 high salinity levels, and high fish densities to create 
 an (surrounding conditions) good for the Pfiesteria outbreak. 
 Attention immediately focused on the large (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) 
 industry in the area as the most probable source of 
 phosphorus pollution in the waters. 
 The Chesapeake Bay Program is a federal, state, 
 and local effort to coordinate clean up the Chesapeake Bay. This program has been working to improve 
 water quality throughout the bay area. One focus of 
 the program has been on farming-based nutrient management. In 1989, the Maryland Cooperative Extension 
 began a (something you choose to do, but is not required) program to get growers to adopt nutrient management plans for their land. Adoption of 
 nutrient management guidelines secures/makes sure of that growers 
 will credit all nutrient sources (commercial and animal waste), when making application decisions. Combining source information with information from soil 
 tests, growers only apply that level of (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) necessary to reach their yield goals. If followed, this management plan would lessen farming-based nonpoint 
 source pollution from excess nutrient applications. 
 At the time the nutrient management program was 
 being put into use, concerns over excess nitrogen 
 applications were most important. Common soil science 
 wisdom was that phosphorus runoff could be controlled by controlling (materials that sink in liquids). So, nutrient management plans were written to limit the amount of 
 nitrogen applied (often resulting in over application of 
 phosphorus from animal waste by as much as 100%). 
 In the early 1990s, research began to suggest that in 
 very high phosphorus situations (material that sinks in liquid) control was 
 not enough to contain phosphorus. When the phosphorus level in the soil reaches high levels, dissolved 
 phosphorus could runoff fields, even when (materials that sink in liquids) 
 were controlled. For certain soils, nutrient management plans needed to address both nitrogen and phosphorus loads. To the (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) industry, this meant that 
 application of (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) as a nutrient source could 
 be greatly stopped. This could lead to excess amounts of (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) on some farms. What's more, 
 many farms now using (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) would have 
 
 D. Parker/Agricultural Money flow 24 (2000) 23-3/ 
 
 25 
 
 to switch to commercial (material that makes plants grow better)s to (accomplish or gain with effort) the necessary nutrient balance. This would involve switching 
 from an mostly free source of (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.), to having 
 to buy commercial nitrogen. There was a great 
 deal of (fighting force/bad feelings) by many growers to (without being forced) 
 putting into use phosphorus based nutrient management 
 plans. The Maryland Water Quality Improvement Act 
 of 1998 (WQIA) will require all growers to put into use nutrient management plans that think about/believe both 
 nitrogen and phosphorus in their recommendations. 
 
 already have nutrient management plans (Maryland 
 Cooperative Extension Service, 1997). So, the 
 WQIA will require that an added 1.2 million 
 areas of land put into use plans. These plans can be written by 
 private consultants, Maryland Cooperative Extension, 
 or growers that have been certified. The expected cost 
 to write these added/more plans is about $6.62 
 million. The plans will need to be updated every 
 few years. For some growers these added/more costs 
 may be offset by added/more (money made/good things received) from improved 
 management. 
 
 3. Farming-based hits/affects of water quality 
 regulation 
 
 3.2. (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers and users of (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) litter 
 
 The WQIA tries to create (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) and 
 other benefits to the Chesapeake Bay through reductions in nonpoint source nutrient pollution. This 
 paper carefully studies the money-based effects of the WQIA 
 on farming-based users of (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) (commercial (material that makes plants grow better)s or animal poop/fertilizers) for land computer program, and 
 on Maryland's (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers. The WQIA needs/demands 
 all growers to get and follow a nutrient management plan. The plans will control the amounts of 
 (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) (nitrogen and phosphorus) that may be applied to cropland. Maryland's large (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) industry 
 is mainly located in a small area on the Eastern Shore 
 of the Chesapeake Bay. The high densities of the industry will force it to find other choices to local land 
 application for some share of the (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material). This 
 paper thinks about/believes three other choices to local land application of (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (related to trash or other things on the ground): (mix of dead leaves, manure, etc.) for wholesale and 
 retail markets, energy (changing from one form, state, or state of mind to another), and transport to 
 alternative farming-based lands out of the area. The net 
 money-based effects for each of these other choices are 
 guessed along with some discussion of the distribution of the hits/effects. Recognition of the distribution of 
 the hits/effects allows us to test the (possibility of/possible happening of)  different policies to lessen the bad effects. Added/more 
 sections of the WQIA are discussed in terms of their 
 ability to shift the distribution of the hits/effects or to 
 provide partial payment to those most affected. 
 3.1. All crop growers 
 Almost all crop growers in Maryland will be 
 needed/demanded to have and put into use nutrient management 
 plans. Nearly 1 million areas of land of Maryland cropland 
 
 High concentration in the (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) industry has lead 
 to county level excesses of the amounts of available 
 (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) from animal waste. As a base case, assume 
 that all (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) is now applied as a crop nutrient source within the county of origin. (putting into) use of the WQIA will limit the amount of (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) litter 
 that can be used in any given county and, this way, require 
 that some (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) be put to alternative uses. The 
 other choice uses to in-county land application that will 
 be thought about/believed are: compost, energy production, and 
 transportation for land application outside the county 
 of origin. 
 The change in value of (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) resulting from 
 the WQIA can this way be broken into two parts; the 
 changes in value for in-county land applications, and 
 the added/more changes in value under each of the three 
 other choice use pictures/situations. The changes in value for 
 in-county land application will remain constant across 
 the three other choice use pictures/situations. 
 3.2.1. Guessing amounts of excess (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) litter 
 Information on the total number of areas of land now 
 receiving (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) is combined with guesses of 
 land restrictions under the WQIA to decide/figure out the 
 amount of excess (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) (that amount which can 
 no longer be used for in-county land application). Soil 
 test data from the University of Maryland's Soil Testing Lab are used to guess the number of areas of land of 
 cropland with lots of levels of phosphorus. There 
 is concern that the University of Maryland's Laboratory tests represent a (along with something else/related to something else) high number 
 of soils receiving animal poop/fertilizers and, therefore, this 
 data may overestimate the percentage of areas of land in 
 each county with high levels of phosphorus. So, 
 
