 this analysis may overestimate the hits/effects of the 
 WQIA. 
 Since final rules are not yet available and 
 (good) enough information on the hits/effects of the proposed 
 rules are not available, some simplifying ideas (you think are true) concerning soil phosphorus test levels and 
 nutrient management recommendations are made. 
 For this analysis, assume that nitrogen based nutrient management plans will be needed/demanded for all land 
 with soil phosphorus test values below some pre-set 
 highest value. For land above this level, the addition 
 of phosphorus will not be allowed. 1 The money-based 
 hits/effects at five controlled soil phosphorus levels are 
 guessed: 50 (low), 100 (medium), 150 (best), 
 200 (high), 300 (too much/too many). 
 The first step in guessing the expected amounts 
 of excess (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) is to guess how many areas of land 
 of in-county cropland will be (able to be picked/able to participate) to receive (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material). This is combined with information on the 
 amount of (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) produced in each county to 
 guess the amount of (trash or other things on the ground) that could be used for 
 in-county land application. This number is (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) 
 to account for the fact that not every crop grower 
 will choose to use (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) over commercial 
 (material that makes plants grow better)s. For the Lower Shore (the major (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) 
 production area), it is assumed that 20% of the 
 (able to be picked/able to participate) crop land will not use (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material). This 
 number is increased to 40% for all other Maryland 
 counties. Fig. 1 shows the amounts of (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) litter 
 that will be used as an in-county crop nutrient source 
 under each controlled soil phosphorus level. As the 
 phosphorus restriction is relaxed (moving towards 
 300), the amount of in-county (layer of leaves, twigs, etc., on the ground) use increases. 
 Land with lots of soil phosphorus levels will 
 not be permitted to add any added/more phosphorus. 
 So, in the long run (15-30 years) land with lots of soil phosphorus levels will see phosphorus levels 
 drop. Eventually all cropland will again be available 
 for (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (related to trash or other things on the ground) (online or paper form that asks for a job, money, admission, etc.). The long run, in-county 
 It is expected that the final rules will require the use of a phosphorus index on lands above the pre-set soil phosphorus test level. Application of the phosphorus index is expected 
 to allow some unknown amount of land above this level to apply phosphorus. So, the ideas (you think are true) used in this analysis lead 
 to overestimates of the amount of land for which no phosphorus, 
 and so no (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) Jitter, will be allowed. Therefore, this analysis 
 overestimates the money-based effects at any given soil phosphorus 
 test level. 
