 4. Distribution of hits/effects 
 The distribution of costs between groups of growers may change/differ  significantly across the other choice use 
 pictures/situations. In the cases of (mix of dead leaves, manure, etc.) and energy production, most of the costs are almost certain 
 to be carried by the (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers. A small number 
 of growers may still be able to use (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) on 
 their own fields and these growers may see little or 
 no hit/effect. What's more, some (trash or other things on the ground) will be used on 
 other fields within the county. This (trash or other things on the ground) will produce 
 (material that makes plants grow better) savings. It is unclear who will benefit from 
 those (material that makes plants grow better) savings. If a strong market for (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) 
 litter were to arise, the (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers could capture 
 the (material that makes plants grow better) savings from the in-county use. If a weak 
 market exists, the benefits from the (material that makes plants grow better) savings 
 may go to the crop grower. 
 For the transport of (trash or other things on the ground) for land application outside the county option, it is less clear who will carry/hold the 
 costs and who will get the benefits (of (material that makes plants grow better) 
 savings). If a strong market rises, then (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers will (take control of) much of the (material that makes plants grow better) savings. Under 
 these market conditions, (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers would bear 
 the net costs shown in Fig. 3 (i.e. $50 000 for a phosphorus soil test restriction at 150), and crop growers 
 will mostly break-even. If there is a weak market 
 for (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material), (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers could bear much higher costs, while crop growers could make 
 significant (money made/good things received). With a weak market for (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (layer of leaves, twigs, etc., on the ground), at the phosphorus soil test restriction of 150 picture/situation, (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers could face costs of up to $4.7 
 million while crop growers would get benefits of 
 $3.8 million. This doubt suggests a need to provide (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers either money-based helper  or help in developing a competitive market for (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) 
 litter as a (material that makes plants grow better) source outside its county of origin. 
 
 5. Actions to lessen WQIA hits/affects 
 The WQIA has a few sections that partially 
 lessen the money-based effects of needing/ordering nutrient 
 
 30 
 
 D. Parker/Agricultural Money flow 24 (2000) 23-31 
 
 management. To offset the costs of having nutrient 
 management plans written, growers can apply for a 
 cost share of 50%, up to $3 per area of land. What's more, 
 there are money to increase the number of Maryland 
 Cooperative Extension personnel who help in writing 
 plans. 
 The major expense to (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers will be buying added/more commercial (material that makes plants grow better) for producing 
 their crops (almost 75% of the net costs shown earlier). The WQIA provides for a 50% tax credit, up 
 to $4500 per grower per year for up to 3 years, to 
 help offset the costs of switching from (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) litter 
 to commercial (material that makes plants grow better). 
 The WQIA also does three things that attempt to help in the creation of a strong market for (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material). 
 (1) To help the flow of information in the market 
 (help willing buyers find willing sellers), an animal 
 poop/fertilizer matching service will be set up at the Maryland Department of Farming. This service will 
 allow buyers and sellers to call a toll free telephone 
 number and be matched with others in their area who 
 are looking to sell or buy (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material). (2) To help offset the costs of converting from commercial (material that makes plants grow better) 
 to (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material), the WQIA provides a 100% tax deduction for the costs of poop/fertilizer spreading equipment 
 in their year of (instance of buying something for money). This should help reduce 
 the high entry cost (blocking thing) to use of animal poop/fertilizers. 
 (3) The WQIA provides money to match a (something you choose to do, but is not required) 
 industry (thing that's given/work that's done) to (help increase/show in a good way) (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (related to trash or other things on the ground) movement. The (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) Litter Transport Pilot Project will 
 use these money to cost share, up to $20 c 1 , the costs 
 of moving (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (bedding material) from (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growing 
 places/locations to alternative uses. These money should provide 
 an extra measure of (money made/good thing received) to the (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) (related to trash or other things on the ground) market 
 that may help to pay crop growers for some of 
 the doubt involved in changing (material that makes plants grow better) sources. 
 
 6. Ends/end results 
 Overall, the WQIA does a good job of balancing 
 the need for improvements in (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) quality 
 with the need for Maryland to maintain a healthy 
 farming-based (process of people making, selling, and buying things). While the Act tries to lessen some of its hits/effects on (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) growers with 
 cost share programs and market stimulation, there is 
 still the (possibility of/possible happening of)  some (compared to other things) large money-based 
 hits/effects on some growers. Some hits/effects not yet con- 
 
 sidered include; the possibility of changes in cropping 
 patterns that may arise as a result of a move/change in the 
 relative costs of different (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.), the hits/effects on 
 other animal operations (specifically dairy) in other 
 parts of the state, the hits/effects on organic producers, 
 and the hits/effects on the (plant-related) industry. 
 
